<DIV1 N="3" TYPE="sermon">
<PB N="75" REF="005885_0086_1027605F65F4CFE8">
<HEAD>SERMON III.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Blind BARTIMEUS.</HEAD>
<EPIGRAPH>
<BIBL>MARK X. 52.</BIBL>
<Q><HI>And Je&s;us &s;aid unto him, Go thy way thy Faith hath made thee whole. And immediately he received his Sight, and followed Je&s;us in the Way.</HI></Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P>WHEN the Apo&s;tle <HI>Peter</HI> was re|commending Je&s;us of <HI>Nazareth,</HI> in one of his Sermons to the <HI>Jews,</HI> he gave him a &s;hort, but withal a glorious and exalted Character, <HI>viz. That he went about doing Good.</HI>&mdash;He <HI>went about, i. e.</HI> He &s;ought <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of doing Good&mdash;It was his Meat and Drink to do the Works of him that &s;ent him, whil&s;t the Day of his publick Admini&s;tration la&s;ted.&mdash;Ju&s;tly was he &s;tiled by the Prophet, the Sun of Righteou&s;ne&s;s&mdash;For, as the Sun in the natural Firmament, diffu&s;es his quickening and reviving Beams through the Univer&s;e, &s;o wherever this Sun of Righteou&s;|ne&s;s,
<PB N="76" REF="005885_0087_10276060EC44D708">
the ble&s;&s;ed Je&s;us aro&s;e, he aro&s;e with Healing under his Wings.&mdash;He was indeed a Prophet like unto <HI>Mo&s;es,</HI> and proved, that he was that Me&s;&s;iah which was to come into the World, by the Miracles which he wrought; tho' with this material Difference, the Mira|cles of <HI>Mo&s;es,</HI> agreeable to the Old Te<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">ment Di&s;pen&s;ation, were Miracles of Judgment<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> the Miracles of Je&s;us, who came to bear our Sickne&s;&s;es, and heal our Infirmities, were Mi|racles of Mercy; and were wrought not only for the Cure of Peoples Bodies, but al&s;o for th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> Conver&s;ion of their precious and immortal Souls.&mdash;Sometimes one and the &s;ame Per&s;on was the Subject of both the&s;e Mercies&mdash;A glo|rious Proof of this, we have in the miraculous Cure wrought upon a poor blind Beggar, nam|ed <HI>Bartimeus,</HI> who is to be the Subject of the following Di&s;cour&s;e, and to whom the Words of the Text refer.&mdash;<HI>Je&s;us &s;aid unto him, go thy way; thy Faith hath made thee whole. And immediately he received his Sight, and followed Je&s;us in the Way.</HI></P>
<P>My De&s;ign is, <HI>Fir&s;t,</HI> to make &s;ome Ob&s;er|vations on the Matter of Fact, as recorded by the Evangeli&s;ts. And then,</P>
<P><HI>Secondly,</HI> To point out the Improvement that may be made of it. May Je&s;us &s;o ble&s;s it, that every &s;piritually blind Hearer, may re|ceive
<PB N="77" REF="005885_0088_1027606532A6B878">
his Sight, and after the Example of <HI>Bartimeus, follow Je&s;us in the Way!</HI></P>
<P>If we would take a View of the whole Sto|ry, we mu&s;t go back to the 46th Ver&s;e of this Chapter&mdash;<HI>And</HI> they, <HI>i. e.</HI> our Lord and his Di&s;ciples (who, we find by the Context, had been conver&s;ing together) <HI>came to Jericho</HI>&mdash;A Place devoted by <HI>Jo&s;hua</HI> to the Cur&s;e of God&mdash;And yet, even this Place yields Con|verts to Je&s;us&mdash;<HI>Zaccheus</HI> had been called out of it formerly; and <HI>Bartimeus,</HI> as we &s;hall hear by and by, in all Probability, was called now.&mdash;For &s;ome Good may come even out of <HI>Nazareth</HI>&mdash;Chri&s;t him&s;elf was born there, and his &s;overeign Grace can reach, and overcome the wor&s;t of People, in the very wor&s;t of Places.&mdash;<HI>Je&s;us come to Jericho</HI>&mdash;Let not his Mini&s;ters, if Providence points out their Way, &s;hun go|ing to &s;eemingly the mo&s;t unlikely Places to do Good&mdash;Some cho&s;en Ve&s;&s;els may be there|in&mdash;Je&s;us and his Di&s;ciples came to <HI>Jericho</HI>&mdash;They were <HI>Itinerants;</HI> and, as I have frequently ob&s;erved, &s;eldom &s;tayed long in a Place&mdash;Not that this is any Argument again&s;t the &s;tated Settlement of particular Pa&s;tors over particular Pari&s;hes.&mdash;But however, our Lord's Practice, in this Re&s;pect, gives a Kind of a Sanction to <HI>i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">n<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ant</HI> Preaching, when Per&s;ons are pro|perly called to, and qualified for, &s;uch an Em|ploy.&mdash;And I believe we may venture to af|firm
<PB N="78" REF="005885_0089_102760696F09F630">
(tho' we would by no means pre&s;cribe, or dictate to the Holy One of <HI>I&s;rael</HI>) that, whenever there &s;hall be a general Revival of Religion in any Country, <HI>itine<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ant</HI> Preaching will be more in Vogue.&mdash;And it is to be fear|ed, that tho&s;e who condemn it now, merely on Account of the Meanne&s;s of its Appear|ances, would have joined with the Self-righ|teous Scribes and Phari&s;ees, in condemning even the Son of God him&s;elf, for &s;uch a Practice.&mdash;</P>
<P><HI>And as he went out of Jericho with his Di&s;ciples,</HI> &s;ays the Evangeli&s;t, <HI>and a great Number of People,</HI> <GAP DESC="foreign">, a great Num|ber of the Mob, or Rabble, as the High-Prie&s;ts of that Generation termed them&mdash;For the&s;e were the con&s;tant Followers of Je&s;us of <HI>Nazareth.</HI>&mdash;It was the Poor that received his Go&s;pel, the common People that heard him gladly, and followed him from Place to Place&punc;&mdash;Not that all who followed him, were his true Di&s;ciples&mdash;No, &s;ome followed him only for his Loaves, others out of Curio&s;ity; tho' &s;ome undoubtedly followed to hear, and be edified by the gracious Words that proceeded out of his Mouth. Je&s;us knew this, and was al&s;o &s;en&s;ible, how di&s;plea&s;ing this crowding after him was to &s;ome of the Rulers of the <HI>Jewi&s;h</HI> Church; who, upon every Occa&s;ion, were ready to &s;ay, <HI>have <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ny of the Scribes a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">d Pha|ri&s;ees believed on him?</HI> But notwith&s;tanding&punc;
<PB N="79" REF="005885_0090_1027606AF4DD91C0">
I do not hear of our ble&s;&s;ed Lord's &s;ending them Home but once; and that was, after they ha<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">een with him three Days, and had no|thing left to eat&mdash;No; he &s;aw they were as Sheep, having no Shepherd, and therefore had Compa&s;&s;ion on them, and taught them.&mdash;A &s;ufficient Warrant this, for Go&s;pel-Mini&s;ters to preach to poor Souls, that follow to hear the Word, whatever Principle their coming may proceed from.&mdash;At the &s;ame Time, they &s;hould caution People again&s;t thinking them|&s;elves Chri&s;tians, <HI>becau&s;e</HI> they follow Chri&s;t's Mini&s;ters&mdash;This our Lord frequently did.&mdash;For there are many that followed Je&s;us, and now follow his Mini&s;ters, and hear them gladly; nay, perhaps, do many Things, as <HI>Herod</HI> did&punc; who, 'tis to be feared, will never follow them into the Kingdom of Heaven.&mdash;Much People followed Je&s;us h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">e out of <HI>Jericho,</HI> but how many of them were offended in him; and af|terwards, it may be, cried out, <HI>Crucify him&punc; Crucify him.</HI>&mdash;Who wou'd depend on Popu|larity? It is like the Morning Cloud, or early Dew, that pa&s;&s;eth away&mdash;But what a Pre&s;s, and &s;eemingly continued Hurry of Bu&s;ine&s;s, did the ble&s;&s;ed Je&s;us live in!&mdash;He could not be hid&mdash;Go where he wou'd, much People followed him&mdash;He had &s;carce Time to eat Bread.&mdash;Happy is it for &s;uch&punc; who are called out to act in a publick Station in the Church, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">nd to be more abundant in Labours, that
<PB N="80" REF="005885_0091_1027606DDBBDAF40">
their Je&s;us has trod in this dangerous Path be|fore them.&mdash;Popularity is a fiery Furnace&mdash;And no one but he, that kept the three Chil|dren amid&s;t <HI>Nebuchadnezzar'</HI>s Flames, can pre&s;erve popular Mini&s;ters from being hurt by it&mdash;But we can do all Things, thro' Chri&s;t &s;trengthening us&mdash;And I have often thought, that there is one Con&s;ideration &s;ufficient to extingui&s;h, or moderate at lea&s;t, any Exce&s;s of Joy, and &s;elf Complacence, which the mo&s;t popular Preacher may feel, when followed even by the greate&s;t Multitudes; and that is this, <HI>viz.</HI> <Q>How many of the&s;e Hearers will go away, without receiving any &s;a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ing Bene|fit by my Preaching; nay, how many, it may be, will only have their Damnation encrea&s;ed by it!</Q>&mdash;As we find many &s;hall &s;ay at the Great Day, <HI>Ha&s;t thou not taught in our Streets,</HI> to whom Je&s;us &s;hall an&s;wer, <HI>Verily I kn<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">w yo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> not.</HI>&mdash;But to proceed&mdash;<HI>As our Lord went out of Jericho with his Di&s;ciples, and a great Number of People, blind Bartimeus; i. e.</HI> the Son of <HI>Timeus, &s;at by the Highway-&s;ide, beg|ging.</HI> It &s;hou'd &s;eem that he was a noted, tho' by no means what we commonly call, a &s;turdy Beggar; having no other Way, as he had lo&s;t his Sight, to get his Bread&mdash;His Ca&s;e was &s;till the more pitiable, if he was, as &s;ome think the Name imports, the blind Son of a blind Father. It may be, he begged for his Father, and him&s;elf too&mdash;And if &s;o, then
<PB N="81" REF="005885_0092_1027606F83B2AF90">
